        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Cardiac Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Sep 12 2016</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">CT for Assessment of Thrombosis and Pulmonary Embolism in Multiple Stages of Single-Ventricle Palliation: Challenges and Suggested Protocols</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Maryam</span> <span property="familyName">Ghadimi Mahani</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#325f53404b535f55725f57561c475f5b515a1c575647" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="4825293a3129252f08252d2c663d25212b20662d2c3d">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Prachi P.</span> <span property="familyName">Agarwal</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Cynthia K.</span> <span property="familyName">Rigsby</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Jimmy C.</span> <span property="familyName">Lu</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Soudabeh</span> <span property="familyName">Fazeli Dehkordy</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Robyn A.</span> <span property="familyName">Wright</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">BA, ARRT</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Adam L.</span> <span property="familyName">Dorfman</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Rajesh</span> <span property="familyName">Krishnamurthy</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">36</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">5</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2016150233" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2016150233</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The total cavopulmonary connection (TCPC), or Fontan procedure, diverts systemic venous blood directly into the pulmonary arteries and is the palliative surgery of choice for patients with a wide variety of congenital heart diseases with single-ventricle physiologic characteristics. Pulmonary embolism and thrombosis are known complications and are among the major causes of morbidity and mortality in patients after TCPC. Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging is usually performed for postoperative evaluation of patients after single-ventricle repair; however, screening for thrombosis or embolism with MR imaging is not always feasible because of the emergent nature of the clinical presentation or because of artifacts from metallic devices or coils. Computed tomographic (CT) angiography is an effective method for diagnosing pulmonary embolism in children. However, because of altered hemodynamics after single-ventricle palliation, there are unique challenges in achieving optimal opacification of the pulmonary arteries and Fontan circuit that can result in nondiagnostic CT angiographic studies or erroneous image interpretation. Radiologists should be familiar with the multiple stages of single-ventricle palliation, understand the technique for performing pulmonary CT angiography at each stage, and recognize common pitfalls in obtaining and interpreting pulmonary CT angiographic images in patients who have undergone single-ventricle repair.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150233">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150233">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig1a.jpeg" height="1767" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Hypoplastic left heart syndrome and stage 1 Norwood procedure. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of hypoplastic left heart syndrome shows the hypoplastic left ventricle and aorta <i>(Ao)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery. <b>(b)</b> Drawing shows the Norwood procedure, in which the main pulmonary artery is divided from the branch pulmonary artery <i>(1)</i>, and a central shunt (in this case, a modified Blalock-Taussing-Thomas shunt) <i>(2)</i> is placed to provide blood flow for the lungs. A Sano shunt may also be used. The root of the divided main pulmonary artery is used to reconstruct the neoaorta <i>(neoA) (3)</i>. An atrial septectomy provides unobstructed pulmonary venous return to the right and left ventricles <i>(4)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig1b.jpeg" height="1767" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Hypoplastic left heart syndrome and stage 1 Norwood procedure. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of hypoplastic left heart syndrome shows the hypoplastic left ventricle and aorta <i>(Ao)</i>. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery. <b>(b)</b> Drawing shows the Norwood procedure, in which the main pulmonary artery is divided from the branch pulmonary artery <i>(1)</i>, and a central shunt (in this case, a modified Blalock-Taussing-Thomas shunt) <i>(2)</i> is placed to provide blood flow for the lungs. A Sano shunt may also be used. The root of the divided main pulmonary artery is used to reconstruct the neoaorta <i>(neoA) (3)</i>. An atrial septectomy provides unobstructed pulmonary venous return to the right and left ventricles <i>(4)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig2.jpeg" height="1798" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Drawing shows stage 2 of single-ventricle palliation, during which a superior cavopulmonary shunt is created with the bidirectional Glenn procedure. The existing systemic-to-pulmonary arterial shunt is taken down <i>(1)</i>, and an end-to-side anastomosis is created between the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA) (2)</i>. The <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> is also divided from the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. Because the right pulmonary artery is not divided from the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>, flow from the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> also travels to the LPA. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig3.jpeg" height="1798" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Drawing shows stage 2 of single-ventricle palliation, during which a cavopulmonary shunt is created with the hemi–Fontan procedure. The existing systemic-to-pulmonary arterial shunt is taken down <i>(1)</i>. The cavopulmonary shunt is made by creating an atriopulmonary anastomosis between the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA)</i> and by using a barrier (usually a homograft) to separate the blood flow from the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> from the rest of the right atrium <i>(2)</i>. Note that in this procedure, the continuity of the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and right atrium is preserved, as opposed to in the bidirectional Glenn procedure. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig4.jpeg" height="1741" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Drawing shows stage 3 (the final stage) of single-ventricle palliation with the lateral tunnel Fontan procedure. A tunnel made of <abbr title="polytetrafluoroethylene">PTFE</abbr> that incorporates the lateral wall of the right atrium is created inside the right atrium (arrowheads) and directs blood from the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> and <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> into the right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA)</i>, bypassing the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig5.jpeg" height="1741" width="1498" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Drawing shows stage 3 (the final stage) of single-ventricle palliation with the extracardiac Fontan procedure. The superior aspect of the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> is divided from the right atrium and connected to a <abbr title="polytetrafluoroethylene">PTFE</abbr> conduit (arrowhead), which is connected to the right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA)</i>. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig6a.jpeg" height="719" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Imaging pitfalls in a 20-year-old man with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who underwent a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure and presented with shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries (arrows), which were interpreted as pulmonary emboli by the emergency department radiologist. Contrast material was injected from the left upper extremity, and at image acquisition, the left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were not yet opacified (as opposed to the right lower lobe branch pulmonary arteries). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows a flow artifact in the central pulmonary artery (*), a finding that was considered to be a pulmonary embolism since the unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were thought to represent evidence of a pulmonary embolism. <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta (<i>Ao</i>; arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig6b.jpeg" height="737" width="910" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Imaging pitfalls in a 20-year-old man with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who underwent a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure and presented with shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries (arrows), which were interpreted as pulmonary emboli by the emergency department radiologist. Contrast material was injected from the left upper extremity, and at image acquisition, the left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were not yet opacified (as opposed to the right lower lobe branch pulmonary arteries). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows a flow artifact in the central pulmonary artery (*), a finding that was considered to be a pulmonary embolism since the unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were thought to represent evidence of a pulmonary embolism. <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta (<i>Ao</i>; arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig6c.jpeg" height="737" width="965" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Imaging pitfalls in a 20-year-old man with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who underwent a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure and presented with shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries (arrows), which were interpreted as pulmonary emboli by the emergency department radiologist. Contrast material was injected from the left upper extremity, and at image acquisition, the left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were not yet opacified (as opposed to the right lower lobe branch pulmonary arteries). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows a flow artifact in the central pulmonary artery (*), a finding that was considered to be a pulmonary embolism since the unopacified left lower lobe pulmonary arteries were thought to represent evidence of a pulmonary embolism. <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta (<i>Ao</i>; arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig7.jpeg" height="677" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Axial CT angiogram obtained after lower extremity contrast material injection in a 4-year-old girl with a superior cavopulmonary connection. A pseudo filling defect (arrow) is seen in the proximal right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA)</i> due to unopacified blood from the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig8a.jpeg" height="786" width="868" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Imaging pitfall in a 10-year-old girl with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who had undergone a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure. Axial CT angiograms of the chest obtained in the early <b>(a)</b> and delayed <b>(b)</b> phases show an apparent filling defect (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the early phase, a result of sluggish flow in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>–Fontan pathway. This finding mimics thrombosis and resolved on the delayed image obtained 1 minute after injection of contrast material (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig8b.jpeg" height="786" width="907" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Imaging pitfall in a 10-year-old girl with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who had undergone a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure. Axial CT angiograms of the chest obtained in the early <b>(a)</b> and delayed <b>(b)</b> phases show an apparent filling defect (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the early phase, a result of sluggish flow in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>–Fontan pathway. This finding mimics thrombosis and resolved on the delayed image obtained 1 minute after injection of contrast material (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig9a.jpeg" height="2078" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Use of bolus tracking in a 10-year-old girl who had undergone Fontan palliation. A timing bolus technique is not preferred because of the variability of flow velocities in patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiograms show the <abbr title="region of interest">ROI</abbr> in the left pulmonary artery (arrows). Graph indicates peak enhancement in the region of interest versus time. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows the neoaorta <i>(neoA)</i>. It is important to understand the anatomy and physiologic characteristics of the Fontan circulation and not use the neoaorta for bolus tracking.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig9b.jpeg" height="1711" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Use of bolus tracking in a 10-year-old girl who had undergone Fontan palliation. A timing bolus technique is not preferred because of the variability of flow velocities in patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiograms show the <abbr title="region of interest">ROI</abbr> in the left pulmonary artery (arrows). Graph indicates peak enhancement in the region of interest versus time. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT pulmonary angiogram shows the neoaorta <i>(neoA)</i>. It is important to understand the anatomy and physiologic characteristics of the Fontan circulation and not use the neoaorta for bolus tracking.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig10a.jpeg" height="755" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Dual-injection technique with arterial phase imaging in a 5-year-old boy with multiple congenital heart defects (including hypoplastic left ventricle and double-outlet right ventricle) who had undergone multiple cardiac surgeries (including a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure) and presented with frequent oxygen desaturation and recurrent croup. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram obtained with the dual-injection technique shows optimal enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>, and anatomy, as well as a Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis (<i>DKS</i>; arrow). <i>Ao</i> = native aorta, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta <i>(Ao)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows that the lower Fontan pathway is also well-opacified (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig10b.jpeg" height="676" width="876" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Dual-injection technique with arterial phase imaging in a 5-year-old boy with multiple congenital heart defects (including hypoplastic left ventricle and double-outlet right ventricle) who had undergone multiple cardiac surgeries (including a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure) and presented with frequent oxygen desaturation and recurrent croup. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram obtained with the dual-injection technique shows optimal enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>, and anatomy, as well as a Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis (<i>DKS</i>; arrow). <i>Ao</i> = native aorta, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta <i>(Ao)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows that the lower Fontan pathway is also well-opacified (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig10c.jpeg" height="676" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Dual-injection technique with arterial phase imaging in a 5-year-old boy with multiple congenital heart defects (including hypoplastic left ventricle and double-outlet right ventricle) who had undergone multiple cardiac surgeries (including a lateral tunnel Fontan procedure) and presented with frequent oxygen desaturation and recurrent croup. <b>(a)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram obtained with the dual-injection technique shows optimal enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>, and anatomy, as well as a Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis (<i>DKS</i>; arrow). <i>Ao</i> = native aorta, <i>neoA</i> = neoaorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows the native aorta <i>(Ao)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial diagnostic CT pulmonary angiogram shows that the lower Fontan pathway is also well-opacified (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig11a.jpeg" height="730" width="686" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Dual-injection technique in a 10-year-old girl with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who had undergone Fontan palliation. CT was urgently requested for evaluation of a suspected thrombus seen at the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>–Fontan pathway junction at echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced early-phase CT angiogram shows an apparent filling defect (arrow), a result of sluggish flow and unopacified blood in the Fontan pathway, a finding that mimics thrombosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced delayed-phase CT angiograms obtained 1 minute <b>(b)</b> and 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> after administration of contrast material show resolution of the apparent filling defect (arrow). In this case, delayed images were obtained from limited sections of the lower chest to answer the specific clinical question and limit the patient’s radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig11b.jpeg" height="730" width="639" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Dual-injection technique in a 10-year-old girl with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who had undergone Fontan palliation. CT was urgently requested for evaluation of a suspected thrombus seen at the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>–Fontan pathway junction at echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced early-phase CT angiogram shows an apparent filling defect (arrow), a result of sluggish flow and unopacified blood in the Fontan pathway, a finding that mimics thrombosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced delayed-phase CT angiograms obtained 1 minute <b>(b)</b> and 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> after administration of contrast material show resolution of the apparent filling defect (arrow). In this case, delayed images were obtained from limited sections of the lower chest to answer the specific clinical question and limit the patient’s radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig11c.jpeg" height="803" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Dual-injection technique in a 10-year-old girl with hypoplastic left heart syndrome who had undergone Fontan palliation. CT was urgently requested for evaluation of a suspected thrombus seen at the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>–Fontan pathway junction at echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced early-phase CT angiogram shows an apparent filling defect (arrow), a result of sluggish flow and unopacified blood in the Fontan pathway, a finding that mimics thrombosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced delayed-phase CT angiograms obtained 1 minute <b>(b)</b> and 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> after administration of contrast material show resolution of the apparent filling defect (arrow). In this case, delayed images were obtained from limited sections of the lower chest to answer the specific clinical question and limit the patient’s radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig12a.jpeg" height="718" width="879" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Crescentic peripheral thrombus in the Fontan pathway in a 3-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram obtained with one upper extremity injection of contrast material and delayed phase imaging shows a thrombus in the Fontan pathway (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial follow-up CT angiogram obtained 1 month later with the same technique shows worsening of the thrombus (arrow). Eventually, the baffle completely thrombosed despite use of anticoagulation therapy, a finding that was seen at catheter angiography.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig12b.jpeg" height="718" width="896" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Crescentic peripheral thrombus in the Fontan pathway in a 3-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram obtained with one upper extremity injection of contrast material and delayed phase imaging shows a thrombus in the Fontan pathway (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial follow-up CT angiogram obtained 1 month later with the same technique shows worsening of the thrombus (arrow). Eventually, the baffle completely thrombosed despite use of anticoagulation therapy, a finding that was seen at catheter angiography.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig13a.jpeg" height="707" width="878" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Single-injection technique in a 26-year-old man with double-outlet right ventricle and mitral and subaortic stenosis who had undergone Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis, a fenestrated atriopulmonary Fontan procedure, and epicardial dual-chamber pacemaker placement. CT angiography was performed to assess a left ventricular thrombus seen at echocardiography. Axial CT angiograms (obtained in a craniocaudal sequence from <b>a</b> to <b>d</b>) obtained with the single-injection technique show homogeneous enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, right <i>(RV)</i> and left <i>(LV)</i> ventricles, aorta <i>(AO)</i>, and Fontan pathway <i>(F)</i>. <i>APF</i> = atriopulmonary Fontan, <i>DAO</i> = descending aorta, <i>LA</i> = left aorta, <i>T</i> = thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig13b.jpeg" height="707" width="797" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Single-injection technique in a 26-year-old man with double-outlet right ventricle and mitral and subaortic stenosis who had undergone Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis, a fenestrated atriopulmonary Fontan procedure, and epicardial dual-chamber pacemaker placement. CT angiography was performed to assess a left ventricular thrombus seen at echocardiography. Axial CT angiograms (obtained in a craniocaudal sequence from <b>a</b> to <b>d</b>) obtained with the single-injection technique show homogeneous enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, right <i>(RV)</i> and left <i>(LV)</i> ventricles, aorta <i>(AO)</i>, and Fontan pathway <i>(F)</i>. <i>APF</i> = atriopulmonary Fontan, <i>DAO</i> = descending aorta, <i>LA</i> = left aorta, <i>T</i> = thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig13c.jpeg" height="698" width="859" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Single-injection technique in a 26-year-old man with double-outlet right ventricle and mitral and subaortic stenosis who had undergone Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis, a fenestrated atriopulmonary Fontan procedure, and epicardial dual-chamber pacemaker placement. CT angiography was performed to assess a left ventricular thrombus seen at echocardiography. Axial CT angiograms (obtained in a craniocaudal sequence from <b>a</b> to <b>d</b>) obtained with the single-injection technique show homogeneous enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, right <i>(RV)</i> and left <i>(LV)</i> ventricles, aorta <i>(AO)</i>, and Fontan pathway <i>(F)</i>. <i>APF</i> = atriopulmonary Fontan, <i>DAO</i> = descending aorta, <i>LA</i> = left aorta, <i>T</i> = thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150233/asset/images/large/rg.2016150233.fig13d.jpeg" height="698" width="816" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Single-injection technique in a 26-year-old man with double-outlet right ventricle and mitral and subaortic stenosis who had undergone Damus-Kaye-Stansel anastomosis, a fenestrated atriopulmonary Fontan procedure, and epicardial dual-chamber pacemaker placement. CT angiography was performed to assess a left ventricular thrombus seen at echocardiography. Axial CT angiograms (obtained in a craniocaudal sequence from <b>a</b> to <b>d</b>) obtained with the single-injection technique show homogeneous enhancement of the right <i>(RPA)</i> and left <i>(LPA)</i> pulmonary arteries, right <i>(RV)</i> and left <i>(LV)</i> ventricles, aorta <i>(AO)</i>, and Fontan pathway <i>(F)</i>. <i>APF</i> = atriopulmonary Fontan, <i>DAO</i> = descending aorta, <i>LA</i> = left aorta, <i>T</i> = thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150233&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Tomkiewicz-Pajak L, Hoffman P, Trojnarska O, Lipczyńska M, Podolec P, Undas A. Abnormalities in blood coagulation, fibrinolysis, and platelet activation in adult patients after the Fontan procedure. <em>J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg</em> 2014;147(4):1284–1290.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtcvs.2013.06.011">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23891464/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Abnormalities+in+blood+coagulation%2C+fibrinolysis%2C+and+platelet+activation+in+adult+patients+after+the+Fontan+procedure&amp;author=L+Tomkiewicz-Pajak&amp;author=P+Hoffman&amp;author=O+Trojnarska&amp;author=M+Lipczy%C5%84ska&amp;author=P+Podolec&amp;author=A+Undas&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;journal=J+Thorac+Cardiovasc+S